From then on, I've seen him play insanely, train intensely, travel the world, and conquer all. Like many others, I too was brought in by his incredible feat, and have grown to love & support a community of brothers and comrades.

To me, Arslan will always be our pride, our legend, our friend, our hero, and our GOAT.

I still remember it clearly. I was walking past a gaming zone one day, and I saw this grown man there someone‚Äôs relative beating all the little kids in the games and taking their money. He was wasting their tokens and even taking their cash. When I saw him, I thought, ‚ÄúHe can‚Äôt be better than Arslan. No chance.‚Äù

So I went to Arslan‚Äôs street and asked Atif where he was. Atif said he was probably still at school. Anyway, I headed back, and on the way I saw Arslan coming with his friends. I told him, ‚ÄúBro, some older guy is here in our area. He‚Äôs beating all the kids and taking their money, eating up their tokens.‚Äù

Arslan said, ‚ÄúAlright, show me where he is.‚Äù

Me, Arslan, his friend, and a bunch of kids from the street all went together to the gaming zone. That guy was still standing there. I pointed at him and said, ‚ÄúThis is my brother. Beat him if you can, then we‚Äôll admit you‚Äôre the best player.‚Äù

Arslan looked at me like, ‚ÄúWhat is this guy even saying?‚Äù üòÇ
But I knew how Arslan played, he would destroy this man in the first round. And that‚Äôs exactly what happened.

Arslan picked up the stick, started the fight, and the man couldn‚Äôt even handle the first round. He got completely destroyed. All the kids who were getting beaten before were so happy. And Arslan was hardly 12 or 13 at that time, same age as me.

We were all so happy. Arslan became a hero there. That man got so embarrassed. ü§£ü§£ü§£

snippet.textDisplay:
At 11:20 , he is completely right. Around 10‚Äì12 years ago, arcades in Pakistan were definitely not a safe place for kids. Most of the people who went there were uneducated and behaved in really inappropriate ways. They usually came in groups, and even if someone went alone, they would quickly join others like themselves. Harassing kids was almost a normal thing for them.
You‚Äôd be playing, fully focused on the screen, and suddenly someone would touch you from behind in a weird or inappropriate way. When you turned around, you‚Äôd see 5‚Äì6 older boys (around 17‚Äì22 years old) laughing like it was nothing. On top of that, the place was full of smoke ‚Äî guys were smoking openly, using bad language, and doing all kinds of nonsense. And because you didn‚Äôt want to lose your coin, you had to just tolerate it. This happened almost every single time.
In all the years I went to arcades, I can barely remember seeing even one well-mannered, well-dressed, or educated person. Most of them were just loafers wasting time, smoking, and bothering others. So yeah parents were just saving their kids but they also couldn't afford PC or something too...

On top of that, the place was full of smoke ‚Äî guys were smoking openly, using bad language, and doing all kinds of nonsense. And because you didn‚Äôt want to lose your coin, you had to just tolerate it. This happened almost every single time.
In all the years I went to arcades, I can barely remember seeing even one well-mannered, well-dressed, or educated person. Most of them were just loafers wasting time, smoking, and bothering others. So yeah parents were just saving their kids but they also couldn't afford PC or something too...
